# ShellCheck configuration for my-shell project.
#
# Last audited: 2026-04-15. Method: stripped this file entirely, ran
# `scripts/dev/run-shellcheck` locally (shellcheck 0.11.0) and under
# Ubuntu CI via `make test-act` (the apt-packaged shellcheck, older
# series), then kept only the rules that actually still fire.
#
# Rules removed during the audit because they produced zero hits on
# either toolchain — future edits may reintroduce them if a new hit
# lands and the exception is justified:
#   SC2032   Alias can't be invoked via xargs
#   SC2262   Alias definition and usage in same parsing unit
#   SC2263   Multiple unused alias definitions

# SC2139 — "This expands when defined, not when used. Consider escaping."
# shell/*/aliases.* intentionally builds alias bodies that interpolate
# shell state at definition time (e.g. `alias top="htop -s PERCENT_CPU"`
# inside a conditional). The warning is a real warning in other
# contexts; it's disabled project-wide because the alias patterns are
# load-bearing and reviewed by hand. 2-3 hits on both toolchains.
disable=SC2139

# SC2317 — "Command appears to be unreachable."
# Several error-handling `return`/`exit` paths and the `_usage` helper
# patterns in scripts/bin/* look unreachable to shellcheck's simple
# analyzer but are reached via getopts `?` / trap dispatch / sourced
# callers. 3+ hits locally, 9+ hits on Ubuntu CI.
disable=SC2317

# SC2015 — "A && B || C is not if-then-else. C may run when A is true."
# `scripts/dev/ll-compare` and `scripts/dev/ls-compare` use the
# `(cmd) || true` idiom as a best-effort fallback so a failing awk in
# one test case doesn't abort the whole run. Local shellcheck 0.11.0
# no longer flags this pattern; the apt-packaged shellcheck on Ubuntu
# CI (older series) still does, so the disable is required for CI
# green. 0 hits locally, 4 hits on Ubuntu CI.
disable=SC2015
